  "prompt": "Why is 2000 rupee note introduced and the 1000 rupee note is scraped? Why can't 1000 note also be changed to new ones like the 500?",
  "response": "The introduction of the \u20b92000 note and the demonetization of the \u20b91000 note in 2016 were part of a larger government initiative with several stated objectives:\n\n*   **Combating Black Money:** The government argued that high-denomination notes like the \u20b91000 were being used for illegal transactions and hoarding unaccounted wealth. Removing them was intended to flush out this \"black money\" into the formal economy.\n*   **Counterfeit Currency:** High-value notes are more attractive targets for counterfeiters. Removing the \u20b91000 note aimed to reduce the circulation of fake currency.\n*   **Promoting Digital Transactions:** The government wanted to encourage people to use digital payment methods like credit/debit cards, mobile wallets, and online banking. Demonetization created a temporary inconvenience that incentivized people to explore these alternatives.\n*   **Bridging the Cash Gap:** The \u20b92000 note was introduced to quickly remonetize the economy after a large portion of the circulating currency was suddenly removed. It allowed for faster replenishment of the cash supply compared to printing only lower-denomination notes.\n\n**Why not just redesign the \u20b91000 note?**\n\nWhile redesigning the \u20b91000 note was an option, the government chose to demonetize it for the following reasons:\n\n*   **Disrupting Illegal Activities:** A simple redesign wouldn't have achieved the goal of flushing out black money. People holding illegal wealth could have simply exchanged old notes for new ones without any real impact.\n*   **Creating a Stronger Impact:** Demonetization was a shock to the system designed to create a significant impact. It forced people to deposit their old currency in banks, providing authorities with information about their transactions. A simple redesign would not have had the same effect.\n*   **Symbolic Message:** Scrapping the \u20b91000 note sent a strong message about the government's commitment to fighting corruption and illegal activities.\n\n**In summary:**\n\nThe decision to introduce the \u20b92000 note and scrap the \u20b91000 note was a strategic one aimed at achieving multiple objectives beyond simply updating the currency. While a redesign of the \u20b91000 note was possible, it would not have addressed the government's primary goals of combating black money, counterfeit currency, and promoting digital transactions.",
